<DOC><DOCNO> AP900606-0201 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-90 2132EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-East-WestMayor     06-06 0170</FIRST><SECOND>AM-East-West Mayor,0173</SECOND><HEAD>West German Elected Mayor of Leipzig, East Germany</HEAD><DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A West German official was voted inWednesday as new mayor of East Germany's second largest city,Leipzig.   Heinrich Lehmann-Grube, 57, a left-leaning Social Democrat andformer city director of Hanover in West Germany, drew 88 of 118votes in the Leipzig city council.   He was given a leave of absence to run for the job, previouslyheld by Guenter Haedrich, a former member of East Germany's oldCommunist party.   Leipzig, with 550,000 people, is second to East Berlin, with 1.2million residents. Leipzig was the cradle of East Germany'spro-democracy movement.   Lehmann-Grube is the second West German to be chosen mayor of anEast German city since the country's first democratic elections inMarch.   West German businessman Dieter Noll, a member of ChancellorHelmut Kohl's conservative Christian Democratic Union, was electedmayor of the former city of Karl-Marx-Stadt last week, when the citywas officialy renamed Chemnitz. The city population is 308,000.</TEXT></DOC>